<section id="modern-legacy" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Modern Legacy: Disparities and Denouncements</h2>
  <p>Fast forward to 2021: Planned Parenthood publicly denounced Sanger’s eugenic beliefs. Alexis McGill Johnson, the organization’s president, stated, 'Margaret Sanger’s racist alliances and belief in eugenics have caused irreparable damage to the health and lives of Black people, Indigenous people, people of color, people with disabilities, immigrants, and many others' (Vertex AI Search, 2024) (citation unverified).</p>
  <p>Yet the past isn’t neatly buried. Black women, who make up about 13.7% of the female population of childbearing age, account for 38% to 42% of reported abortions in states tracking race data (California Globe, 2026). Critics like Justice Clarence Thomas argue this reflects a lingering eugenic influence, citing Sanger’s ideology as a direct precursor to modern disparities in abortion access and outcomes (California Globe, 2026) (citation unverified).</p>
  <p>Defenders of reproductive rights push back, asserting that access to birth control and abortion empowers women, especially women of color, to reclaim autonomy—a direct rejection of eugenic control. Michelle Williams of Harvard’s School of Public Health notes, 'The eugenics movement has never been about giving women the right to choose… it has been about ripping that autonomy from women deemed inferior' (Research Data). Both sides have evidence; neither fully resolves the tension.</p>
</section>
<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Margaret Sanger’s racist alliances and belief in eugenics have caused irreparable damage." — Alexis McGill Johnson, 2021</p></aside>
<section id="recent-violations" class="reveal">
  <h2>Recent Violations: Echoes of the Past</h2>
  <p>Eugenic practices didn’t vanish with Sanger’s era. Between 2005 and 2011, 148 female prisoners in California were sterilized through tubal ligations without required state approvals (PubMed, 2015). These cases, often targeting women of color, show how reproductive coercion persists under new guises.</p>
  <p>Globally, coerced sterilization remains an issue, often tied to population control policies in marginalized regions. The ideology of 'improving' society through reproductive control hasn’t been eradicated—it’s just adapted. Natasha Furtado Dalomba, MD, sums it up: 'To appreciate the liberation that contraception can provide, one must also recognize and reckon with the oppression and trauma in its history' (Research Data).</p>
</section>
<section id="conclusion-challenge" class="reveal">
  <h2>A Challenge for Today</h2>
  <p>The birth control movement’s eugenic shadow isn’t a relic to be shrugged off. It’s a history that shaped policies, scarred communities, and still colors how reproductive healthcare is accessed and perceived. Disparities in abortion rates, lingering distrust among marginalized groups, and recent sterilization abuses beg a hard question.</p>
  <p>How much of today’s reproductive landscape—its inequities, its blind spots—still echoes that past? This isn’t about guilt or blame. It’s about seeing clearly, and deciding what to do next. Reflect on that.</p>
</section>
